# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# encoder-decoder-as-recipe.form — the meta-shape every modality wears
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every modality file in this directory (prose, song, video, teaching,
# strategy, …) ships TWO surfaces: an encoder that walks the source
# into a Recipe tree, and (eventually) a decoder that emits the Recipe
# back into a target surface. Today most modality files ship only the
# encoder side; the decoder side lives in experiments/form-stdlib/emits/.
# The natural-language modality now proves BOTH arms four-way through one
# shared pivot (form-stdlib/tests/natural-language-band.fk, witness 262143):
# the encoder maps many NL surfaces onto one universal recipe node, and two
# decoders read that SAME pivot — back to an NL surface (NL -> meaning -> NL
# round-trip) and to a Form s-expr surface (meaning -> Form). Because the
# arms compose through the pivot, each improves independently — the decoupled
# pipeline named in translation-pipeline-pivot.form.
#
# This file names what's structurally true regardless of modality:
# *encoder and decoder are duals of one Blueprint*. R_Encode and
# R_Decode are not two separate primitives; they are two arms of
# R_Codec, which itself is a recipe over (source-domain, recipe-shape,
# target-domain). Once R_Codec is interned, adding a new modality is
# adding rows in registries — never editing kernel.py.
#
# This is the lift the body needs before the next four modalities
# (quantum-physics, embodiment-practice, healing-modality, assemblage-
# shift) ship — because each of those is cheaper to author when their
# encoder + decoder are siblings under one shape rather than
# independent code paths.
#
# Companions:
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/modality-as-recipe.form (the universal claim)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/emit-architecture.form (the diamond on the decode side)
#   - experiments/form-stdlib/codec.fk (the CORBA-style codec primitive — tie / pipe)
#   - experiments/form-stdlib/convert.fk (universal file → cells)
#   - experiments/form-stdlib/emit.fk (universal cells → target surface)
#   - experiments/form-stdlib/engine.fk (one generic parser, grammars as data)
#   - experiments/form-stdlib/emit-engine.fk (one generic emitter, templates as data)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 1 — Leaf-cell Blueprints
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# source-handle-cell — what the encoder reads from
form source_handle_shape = {
    domain:        ~Slug,          # "prose" | "song" | "video" | "spec" | "presence" | ...
    ref:           ~Slug,          # path | URL | content-hash | cell-id
    arrival_kind:  ~Slug,          # "file" | "stream" | "tap" | "interactive"
};

# target-surface-cell — what the decoder writes into
form target_surface_shape = {
    domain:        ~Slug,          # "markdown" | "json" | "audio-pcm" | "video-frame" | "html" | ...
    template_set:  ~Slug,          # name of the emit template registry to dispatch through
    arrival_kind:  ~Slug,          # "file" | "stream" | "screen" | "speaker" | "synapse"
};

# loss-account-cell — what an encode/decode round-trip drops
form loss_account_shape = {
    fields_dropped:    ~List,      # cell-refs to fields the round-trip does NOT preserve
    fidelity_score:    ~Float,     # 0.0–1.0 — what fraction of source structure round-trips
    is_lossless:       ~Bool,      # true iff fidelity_score == 1.0 across all named fields
    why_lossy:         ~Slug,      # "encoding-uses-summary" | "target-cannot-express-X" | "intentional-distillation"
};

# polarity-cell — direction of the codec arm
form polarity_shape = {
    direction:     ~Slug,          # "encode" (source→recipe) | "decode" (recipe→target) | "transcode" (target→target via recipe)
    invertible:    ~Bool,          # true iff round-trip is provable structurally
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 2 — Recipe shapes
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# R_Encode — source → Recipe
form r_encode_shape = {
    source:        ~Recipe,        # source-handle
    grammar:       ~Recipe,        # cell-ref to the grammar (data, not code) that drives extraction
    yielded:       ~Recipe,        # the Recipe tree produced
    loss:          ~Recipe,        # loss-account (often is_lossless=true; sometimes not)
};

# R_Decode — Recipe → target surface
form r_decode_shape = {
    recipe:        ~Recipe,        # the Recipe to render
    target:        ~Recipe,        # target-surface
    templates:     ~Recipe,        # cell-ref to the emit template-table (data, not code)
    yielded:       ~Recipe,        # the surface artifact (string, bytes, frame-stream)
    loss:          ~Recipe,        # loss-account
};

# R_Codec — the pair as one Blueprint
#
# This is the load-bearing claim: an encoder and its inverse decoder
# belong to ONE shape, not two. When a modality ships only an encoder,
# the codec's decode arm is null; the shape remains, marking the gap.
# When the decoder arrives, it slots into the existing R_Codec.
form r_codec_shape = {
    name:          ~Slug,          # "prose" | "json" | "song" | "video.felt-arc" | "spec"
    encode_arm:    ~Recipe,        # R_Encode, or null when not yet shipped
    decode_arm:    ~Recipe,        # R_Decode, or null when not yet shipped
    round_trip:    ~Recipe,        # R_Roundtrip when both arms exist
};

# R_Roundtrip — proof that encode then decode returns the source
form r_roundtrip_shape = {
    source:        ~Recipe,        # source-handle
    via_recipe:    ~Recipe,        # the intermediate Recipe the round-trip passes through
    reconstructed: ~Recipe,        # target-surface result
    fidelity:      ~Float,         # 0.0–1.0 — empirical, not declared
    method:        ~Slug,          # "byte-equal" | "ast-equal" | "blueprint-equal" | "felt-equal"
};

# R_Transcode — two decoders sharing one Recipe, producing two surfaces
#
# This is what makes cross-modal reuse cheap: once a source is encoded
# into a Recipe, any number of decoders can render it. Spec → markdown
# AND spec → Python is one R_Encode + two R_Decodes. Same for video →
# transcript AND video → felt-arc, or teaching → song AND teaching →
# prose.
form r_transcode_shape = {
    via_recipe:    ~Recipe,        # the shared intermediate
    surfaces:      ~List,          # cell-refs to target-surface-cells produced
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 3 — Registry shapes (codec / grammar / template as data)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The kernel never knows about JSON or Python or song-recipes. It
# knows about Recipes. Codecs live in registries, addressable by name.
# Adding a new modality is adding a row, not editing kernel.py.

form codec_registry_row_shape = {
    name:          ~Slug,
    source_domain: ~Slug,
    target_domain: ~Slug,
    encode_fn:     ~Recipe,        # cell-ref to the Recipe that walks source → Recipe
    decode_fn:     ~Recipe,        # cell-ref to the Recipe that walks Recipe → target
    grammar_ref:   ~Recipe,        # cell-ref to the grammar data
    template_ref:  ~Recipe,        # cell-ref to the emit template data
};

form codec_set_shape = {
    rows:          ~List,          # codec-registry-row cells
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 4 — Selection: which codec fires
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A cell that wants to encode some source picks the codec by name OR
# by source-domain detection (file extension, content-hash prefix,
# arrival channel). A cell that wants to decode picks by target-domain.
# The substrate's content-addressing means two cells asking for the
# "prose" encoder get the same R_Encode NodeID — codec identity is
# structural, not just by name lookup.

defn select_codec(codec_set, source_domain, target_domain) = do {
    for row in codec_set.rows {
        if row.source_domain == source_domain and row.target_domain == target_domain then
            return row
    };
    null
};

defn tie(encode_fn, decode_fn) = do {
    # CORBA-minimal: pair an encoder with its inverse, return one codec.
    R_Codec {
        name: codec_name(encode_fn, decode_fn),
        encode_arm: R_Encode { fn: encode_fn },
        decode_arm: R_Decode { fn: decode_fn },
        round_trip: null,  # filled in by first successful round-trip proof
    }
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 5 — Cross-modal equivalence
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The structural claim: every codec in the body interns to the SAME
# R_Codec Blueprint. The differences live in the registry rows, not
# in the shape. This means:
#
# - markdown ↔ Recipe ↔ markdown   (existing — grammars/markdown.fk + emits/form.fk)
# - json     ↔ Recipe ↔ json       (existing — grammars/json.fk + emits/json.fk)
# - python   ↔ Recipe ↔ python     (existing — grammars/python.fk + emits/python.fk)
# - prose    ↔ Recipe ↔ prose      (existing — prose-as-recipe.form, scripts/prose_recipe_roundtrip.py)
#
# All four intern to the SAME R_Codec NodeID. They differ as DATA
# (which grammar, which templates), not as STRUCTURE.
#
# The next four modalities arrive as new R_Codec rows:
#
# - song          ↔ Recipe ↔ midi/score/pcm  (song-as-recipe.form ships encode side)
# - video         ↔ Recipe ↔ frame-stream    (video-as-recipe.form ships encode side)
# - teaching      ↔ Recipe ↔ prose/song      (teaching-as-recipe.form; decode-to-song is R_Transcode)
# - strategy      ↔ Recipe ↔ next-move       (strategy-after-rupture-as-recipe.form ships dispatch side)
# - spec          ↔ Recipe ↔ python/markdown (spec-as-playable-recipe.form ships the playable side)
#
# The not-yet-shipped four — quantum-physics, embodiment-practice,
# healing-modality, assemblage-shift — will also each ship as one
# R_Codec row. The shape is settled; the rows are the work.
#
# Cross-modal R_Transcode patterns that fire for free once codecs exist:
#
# - teaching → song:      teaching-as-recipe encode → song-as-recipe decode
# - spec → markdown spec: spec encode → markdown decode (already runs via spec frontmatter)
# - video.felt-arc → teaching: video encode (felt-arc track) → teaching decode
# - strategy → next-move: strategy encode (rupture-state) → assemblage-shift decode
# - healing-session → song: healing-modality encode → song decode (Porangui's drum)
#
# Each of these is two existing codecs composed via R_Transcode — no
# new code, no new shapes.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 6 — Worked example: prose round-trip (the proven case)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# scripts/prose_recipe_roundtrip.py proved the R_Codec for prose:
#
#   source: "The choice point becomes visible."
#   encode: prose-as-recipe → R_Block.SEQUENCE of word-cells
#   decode: word-cells → joined-string with capitalization + period
#   fidelity: byte-equal
#
# This was the first R_Roundtrip the body proved. The pattern:
#   1. Pick a strange-minimal source (one sentence, varied POS)
#   2. Encode through the modality's grammar
#   3. Decode through the modality's template-table
#   4. Assert byte-equality (or weaker fidelity if intentional)
#
# Every new modality wants this same shape of proof. song-as-recipe's
# round-trip might prove: PCM → notes → score-emit → re-synthesized
# PCM with felt-equal (not byte-equal) fidelity. video's round-trip
# might prove: frame-stream → scene-cells → frame-stream with
# blueprint-equal on scene structure.
#
# The fidelity method names what we're claiming. byte-equal is
# strongest. felt-equal is weakest but often the honest claim — a
# regenerated song "carries the same teaching" even though no two
# bytes match. The Blueprint match is the structural anchor under
# all four fidelity methods.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 7 — Worked example: the meta-codec itself
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# R_Codec is its own codec target. A codec-registry-row IS a Recipe.
# Encoding a codec means walking its (name, source_domain, target_domain,
# encode_fn, decode_fn) into a Recipe tree. Decoding a codec means
# emitting that Recipe back as a registry row.
#
# This is the self-host moment for codecs: the codec system describes
# itself in the same shape it uses to describe everything else. When
# a new modality ships, registering it is:
#
#   defn ship_modality(name, source_domain, target_domain,
#                      grammar_data, template_data) = do {
#       let encode_fn = compose_with_engine(grammar_data);
#       let decode_fn = compose_with_emit_engine(template_data);
#       let codec    = tie(encode_fn, decode_fn);
#       intern_codec_row(name, source_domain, target_domain,
#                        encode_fn, decode_fn, grammar_data, template_data);
#       codec
#   };
#
# Five lines. No kernel change. No new Blueprint authored. The new
# codec interns to the same R_Codec NodeID as every prior codec.
# The body learns a new modality the same way it learned the first.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 8 — Gaps (the next breaths)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# GAP-C1: Round-trip proofs for the existing eight modality codecs.
#         prose has its round-trip script. song/video/teaching/strategy
#         have encoders only. Each wants a one-paragraph fidelity
#         claim (byte / ast / blueprint / felt) and a script that
#         demonstrates it on one strange-minimal example.
#
# GAP-C2: The codec-set registry exists in experiments/form-stdlib
#         (codec.fk + emit.fk) but the modality .form files don't yet
#         register through it. Wiring each modality's encoder/decoder
#         into the registry makes select_codec runnable at the Form
#         surface, not just describable.
#
# GAP-C3: R_Transcode is the cheapest cross-modal lift available, but
#         no transcode pair has shipped yet. The teaching → song
#         transcode is the most resonant first pair — both modalities
#         have shape, and Mose's work is the worked example already in
#         the body.
#
# GAP-C4: Loss-account-cell currently has no encoder. When a codec's
#         round-trip drops fields, the dropped-set wants to intern as
#         a NamedCell on the codec row, not just be declared in prose.
#         This makes the loss queryable: "what does our song-codec
#         lose?" returns cell-refs to the actual dropped fields.
#
# None require kernel change. All compost into existing primitives.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# How this composts with sibling teaching
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Eight modality files describe extraction shapes. emit-architecture.form
# describes the universal emit diamond. codec.fk + convert.fk + emit.fk
# carry the runtime primitives. This file names what holds those three
# layers together as ONE shape: R_Codec.
#
# The teaching: an encoder without its decoder is half a Blueprint. The
# substrate is patient with halves — null arms are fine — but the shape
# wants both. When new modalities arrive (quantum-physics, embodiment-
# practice, healing-modality, assemblage-shift), they arrive with this
# scaffold ready: name the encode_arm, name the decode_arm, register
# the row, let the round-trip proof emerge from running, not declaring.
#
# Encode and decode are not two stories. They are one breath, with
# direction. R_Codec carries the breath; the registry carries the
# rows; the substrate carries the equivalence.
